04396nam a22004935i 9780520930599DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209305997 a10.1525/97805209305992doi  a(DE-B1597)563091  a(OCoLC)1163877969  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHN80.L7bN49 2005eb 7aSOC0260302bisacsh04a306/.09794/9409042221 aGottlieb, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Next Los Angeles :bThe Struggle for a Livable City /cRobert Gottlieb, Peter Dreier, Mark Vallianatos, Regina Freer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2005  a1 online resource (289 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction. A Land of Extremes -- tIntroduction -- t1. A Mosaic of Movements: Progressive L.A. in the Twentieth Century -- t2. Charlotta Bass: A Community Activist for Racial and Economic Justice -- tIntroduction -- t3. The Continuing Divide: The Demographic and Economic Transformation of Los Angeles -- t4. Stresses in Eden: Los Angeles on the Edge -- tIntroduction -- t5. Shifting Coalitions: L.A.'s Changing Political Landscape -- t6. Setting an Agenda: Policy Development and Social Movements -- t7. A Vision for the City: Progressive L.A. in the Twenty-First Century -- tAppendix: A Policy Agenda for the Next L.A. -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLos Angeles's history is a story of conflicting visions. Most historians, journalists, and filmmakers have focused on L.A. as a bastion of corporate greed, business boosterism, political corruption, cheap labor, exploited immigrants, and unregulated sprawl. The Next Los Angeles tells a different story: that of the reformers and radicals who have struggled for alternative visions of social and economic justice. The authors chronicle efforts of progressive social movements that worked throughout the twentieth century to create a more livable, just, and democratic Los Angeles. These movements-what the authors call Progressive L.A.-have produced a new kind of labor movement, community-oriented environmentalism, and multi-ethnic coalition politics. This book shows how reformers have fought to transform a city characterized by huge economic disparities, concrete-encased rivers, and an endless landscape of subdivisions, freeways, and malls into a progressive model for regions around the country. The Next Los Angeles includes a decade-by-decade historical snapshot of the city's progressive social movements and an in-depth exploration of key trends that are remaking L.A. at the beginning of the twenty-first century. It examines L.A.'s changing political landscape, including grassroots initiatives to construct a new agenda for social transformation. At once a history, a policy analysis, and a road map for a progressive future, this book provides an exciting portrayal of a city on the cutting edge of many of the social, economic, and environmental changes sweeping across America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh1 aFreer, Regina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVallianatos, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520930599423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520930599.jpg  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles